Predicting Tennis Match Winners and Losers¶

AIT580¶

Final Class Project¶

  • Hunter Walden, Kevin Mitchell, Jason Myslewski
  • 13 July 2022

Introduction¶

Is it possible to determine if a tennis player is a winner or a loser based on their match statistics? We set out to determine if this was possible using data from major tennis tournament matches. There are a number of statistics collected on each tennis player as a result of their match. Important statistics include set scores, total points won, winning shots, unforced errors, net points won, break points won, first and second serve percentages and net points won, among many others. In order to find a solution to our question, we determined what statistics were most important and used those for predictive analysis.

The dataset used in this project was derived from the UCI repository. We downloaded both men's and women's match data from all four major tennis tournaments. Overall we had a combined dataset of over 1800 individual records. Each record contained the statistics for a discrete tennis match for both players. Our data cleaning process included renaming columns, dropping unnecessary columns, removing or imputing missing data, removing outliers, and concatenating datasets. We ran classification models to determine predictive ability on match outcome. We examined the output of three different models. We chose Naive Bayes, Logistic Regression, and K-Nearest Neighbors. Overall we were able to predict a winning or losing player based on 4 features with 84% accuracy.

Purpose¶

The purpose of this project is to determine which statistical attributes have the most effect on the outcome (win/loss) of a tennis match, and to predict if a player was a winner or a loser.

Methods¶

  • Tools used include: python, Jupyter Lab, SciKit Learn, pandas, numpy, seaborn, matplotlib.
  • Data cleaning methods include: concatenating, renaming columns, dropping NaN, removing outliers, visualizing data.
  • Predictive analysis methods: logistic regression, naive Bayes, KNN

def column_checker(dfs, colNames):                       
    '''This function will check all the column names in each data frame 
    to match the column names that are listed in the standardized list 
    of column names. 
    
    The function will return the column name that is incorrect, and the 
    number of names that are incorrect for each data frame.
    '''
    num = 0
    for data in dfs:
        rename = []
        for i in range(len(col_names)):
            li = list(data.columns)
            if li[i] != col_names[i]:
                print(f'{li[i]} needs to be fixed')
                rename.append(li[i])
        print(f'{len(rename)} columns need to be renamed in dfs[{num}]')
        print('-----')
        num += 1
        rename.clear()

Now that all 8 data frames are concatenated into one data frame, we need to do some more manipulation. Each row of the data frame contains stats for each match and includes information on both player 1 and player 2. We need to have a data frame where every row is one discrete player and contains an appropriate win/loss label i.e. (1, 0). Below we will divide the columns and create two data frames based on player 1 and player 2. Then we will reindex the columns and rename the columns so that both data frames are identical. We will also add a win/loss label to player two data frame. We will concatenate both player1 and player 2 data frames into one final data frame that will be ready for exploration.

# rename columns in both data frames 
def rename_cols(df):
    '''This function takes the column names of a data frame and returns
    the same data frame with updated column names.
    '''    
    old_cols = list(df.columns)
    new_names = []
    for name in old_cols:
        new = re.sub('\.\d', '', name)
        new_names.append(new)
    d = {key:value for key, value in zip(old_cols, new_names)}
    df2 = df.rename(columns=d)
    return df2

# for each column, determine the IQR, and the upper/lower bound for outliers
IQR = df2.quantile(0.75) - df2.quantile(0.25)
upper_fence = df2.quantile(0.75) + 1.5*(IQR)
lower_fence = df2.quantile(0.25) - 1.5*(IQR)

# apply the mask function to replace the outliers with the mean of each col
df2 = df2.mask((df2 >= upper_fence), other=avg, axis=1)
df2 = df2.mask((df2 <= lower_fence), other=avg, axis=1)

Part 3: Predictive Analysis¶

In [28]:
# initially defining a function to print out stats for the model 
def model_stats(list1_predicted, list2_test):
    '''This function just prints out correct and incorrect 
    percentages for the model and the accuracy score.
    '''
    compare = list(zip(list1_predicted, list2_test))
    right = 0
    wrong = 0
    for pred, act in compare:
        if pred == act:
            right += 1
        elif pred != act: 
            wrong += 1
    return print(f'{right + wrong} total predictions /' 
                 f'\n{right} correct predictions /' 
                 f'\n{wrong} wrong predictions /' 
                 f'\nAccuracy score: {(right)/(right + wrong)}')

Part 4: Conclusion¶

Overall, we see that the logistic regression produces the best or most accurate predictive ability with a best score of 84%. The KNN and Naive Bayes models produce a best accuracy score of 78-79%. The negative aspect of the Naive Bayes model is the very high number of false positives compared to the KNN model.

We believe our logistic regression model would be useful to professional tennis players to see how they might compete against another opponent given their historical and their opponents historical match statistics.
